The first step is to dismantle stereotypes at home and in schools. As a hairdresser who enjoys board games and hiking, I know how powerful play and hands‑on exploration can be. Integrating science into everyday activities—like measuring the growth of plants during a hike or experimenting with color mixing while cutting hair—can spark interest in children regardless of gender. Secondly, mentorship programs that pair young women with female scientists create visible role models; when girls see someone who looks like them succeeding, the path feels less distant. Thirdly, funding agencies must adopt blind review processes and set explicit diversity targets, ensuring that bias does not seep into grant decisions.

